  "prompt": "Is it a bad idea to teach high school for two years before applying to med schools?",
  "response": "Teaching high school before applying to med school can actually have some potential benefits:\n\nPros:\n1. Demonstrates leadership and commitment to education\n2. Provides unique experiences for medical school applications\n3. Can help you save money\n4. Allows time to strengthen your medical school application\n5. Potential teaching/science background can be viewed positively\n6. Opportunity to gain perspective and maturity\n\nPotential Cons:\n1. Slight delay in medical career timeline\n2. Could reduce time for medical school prerequisites/research\n3. Might need to balance teaching with additional coursework\n4. Could interrupt momentum from undergraduate studies\n\nOverall, it's not inherently a bad idea. What matters most is how you use that time to:\n- Maintain strong academic credentials\n- Gain medical/science-related experiences\n- Prepare a competitive medical school application\n- Take necessary prerequisite courses\n\nIf you can balance teaching with medical school preparation, it could be a valuable experience. However, it's recommended to:\n- Consult pre-med advisors\n- Ensure you meet all medical school requirements\n- Keep your long-term goals in focus\n\nEach situation is unique, so carefully evaluate your personal circumstances.",
